{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501074"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:22:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:22:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1717"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1717"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.16,0.04,0.13,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1717"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30418"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1717"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1717"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16360"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"849"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7595"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7625"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42376"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/30418"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents with a two week history of multiple painless nodules on his fingers (Image). There is no itching or pruritis or discharge and he has never had anything like this before. His brother who lives with him also has also noticed similar nodules.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Laser therapy","Oral acyclovir","Topical steroids","Topical nystatin","Topical salicylic acid"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has two superficial lesions on his fingers. These have the typical appearance of warts. Warts are caused by the human papilloma virus and are spread by direct contact. They can be difficult to treat and eradicate. The first line treatment of wart is \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical salicylic acid, \u003C/strong\u003Ea\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ekeratolytic that causes shedding of the outer layer of skin. It works by softening keratin, a protein that forms part of the skin structure. This helps to loosen dry scaly skin making it easier to remove.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaser therapy \u003C/strong\u003Eis a common modality of treatment for painful, large, recalcitrant warts, so is not indicated in the above scenario. It uses an intense beam of light, or laser, to burn and destroy the wart tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther treatment options for cutaneous warts include topical podophyllin, cryotherapy, curettage and cautery (electrosurgery), intralesional bleomycin and photodynamic therapy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough the causative organism for warts is a virus but \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral acyclovir, \u003C/strong\u003Ean antiviral is not indicated for the treatment of common warts. Acyclovir has shown promising results against herpes simplex and varicella zoster virus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical steroids \u003C/strong\u003Ehave an anti-inflammatory and immunosuppressive action. There are no signs of inflammation in the case and the suppressed immunity on contrary might favor the virus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical nystatin \u003C/strong\u003Eis an antifungal drug, it binds to ergosterol in the fungal cell membrane, forms pores in the membrane that lead to death of the fungus. Hence an antifungal drug would not be effective in this case\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The first line treatment of a wart is salicylic acid."],"references":["Kwok CS, Gibbs S, Bennett C, Holland R, Abbott R. Topical treatments for cutaneous warts. Cochrane Database Syst Rev 2012; (9): CD001781.","Nunes EM, Talpe-Nunes V, Sichero L. Epidemiology and biology of cutaneous human papillomavirus. Clinics (Sao Paulo). 2018 Aug 20;73."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16360"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1717"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18377"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18377"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e77fa845-d07d-493d-b4df-5cd03cd3ad87.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e77fa845-d07d-493d-b4df-5cd03cd3ad87.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/16360"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-11-29T08:44:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2022-11-29T08:44:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1717"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30418"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","syn